<a href="http://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/jump?iu=/8900/24.com/Web/DailySun/Sport/PSL_Article&sz=300x250&c=554677465&t=artid%3dae88197b-9706-48a4-a68e-9246a02dca40%26accreditation%3ddaily+sun%26posno%3d2" target="_blank"><img src="http://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/ad?iu=/8900/24.com/Web/DailySun/Sport/PSL_Article&sz=300x250&c=554677465&t=artid%3dae88197b-9706-48a4-a68e-9246a02dca40%26accreditation%3ddaily+sun%26posno%3d2" border="0" alt=""></a>But he stressed that in 25 years of coaching he had never seen anything like that – Bucs doing almost everything right in their Absa Premiership encounter with an out-of-sorts AmaZulu at Orlando Stadium on Saturday, but still unable to get the win. Ntsikelelo Nyauza scored twice – unfortunately once on the wrong end of the pitch. Sredojevic said: “I don’t know whether I should laugh or cry. My players respect the badge – I can tell from their body language and from the effort they put in at training. “What we didn’t do well in this game is get the ball into the net.” Sredojevic said Bucs were still a work in progress, but in his mind he had one million reasons to believe that he was coaching an extraordinary team. He described South Africa as a welcoming country offering so much hospitality but compared Pirates’ performance to a visitor who is given his favourite cup of tea – but gets no sugar. Added Sredojevic: “I regret getting only a point but not the performance. “The point is like a cup of tea without sugar. “It would have been different if there was sugar.” The Serbian mentor had comforting words for misfiring striker Thamsanqa Gabuza and said he had yet to decide if he would go in search of a proven scorer in the transfer market in January. Added Sredojevic: “Our type of football deserves to yield results. But we as the technical team won’t give up. “We will assess the team after the Christmas recess and make a decision at that time.” 
